{{Quote|The odds are ''perfect'' for a hotshot like you showing up ''here.'' And ''that's'' when I'll ''destroy'' you, droid-lover!|Beilert Valance, to Luke Skywalker|<ref name="Star Wars (1977) 27">[[Star Wars (1977) 27|''Star Wars'' (1977) 27]]</ref>}}
'''''Star Wars 27''''' is the twenty-seventh issue of the [[Star Wars Legends|Legends]] [[Star Wars comic books|comic book]] series [[Star Wars (1977)|''Star Wars'']]. It was written by [[Archie Goodwin]], illustrated by [[Carmine Infantino]], and first published on [[June 26]], [[1979]] by [[Marvel Comics]]. The issue features the story "'''Return of the Hunter'''," in which [[Beilert Valance/Legends|Valance]] the [[Bounty hunter/Legends|Hunter]] sets his sights on [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]].

==Publisher's summary==
''Luke is in danger and the only one who can save him is....C3PO ''[''sic'']''?''

==Plot summary==
The [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]] [[Beilert Valance/Legends|Beilert Valance]] has come to the world of [[Feriae Junction/Legends|Feriae Junction]], where he shoots a [[Cantina/Legends|cantina]] patron named [[Marko Tyne]] and then retreats to his agent, [[Skinker]], to collect the [[bounty]]. Valance's payment is a collection of rebuilt [[Droid/Legends|droids]], which he melts into slag with several blasts from his weapon. Forced to live as a [[Cyborg/Legends|cyborg]] due to injuries sustained from an aerial torpedo, Valance has an irrational hatred of all droids and he hunts them down wherever he can find them. Valance's next mission is to find Luke Skywalker. Not only is Luke a droid-owner, but he also apparently treats them as equals, which Valance finds repulsive.

Meanwhile, Luke has taken C-3PO with him in a [[Luke Skywalker's scout craft|blockade runner]] and is mapping out the perimeter of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire's]] most recent blockade. He deftly maneuvers the runner out of the way of an oncoming [[Star Destroyer/Legends|Imperial cruiser]] before making the jump to [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]]. Now Luke has to find a trading post so that he can find parts needed to make repairs to the disabled [[R2-D2/Legends|R2-D2]]. He lands the blockade runner on Junction.

Valance discovers that an Imperial [[Spy/Legends|spy]] has been trying to alert the Empire as to Valance's presence on Junction. Valance, being an Imperial defector, can not let his whereabouts be known, so he shoots the spy, killing him before he can transmit a signal.

Luke and C-3PO arrive at Skinker's salvage yard. They acquire the parts they need, but before long Valance returns and finds them. He tries firing at Luke with his [[Blaster/Legends|blaster]], but Luke deflects the shot with his [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]]. The blast arcs back, striking Valance in the face. Part of his flesh is melted away to reveal [[Cyborg/Legends|cybernetic]] parts beneath. Valance manages to get Luke's blaster and saber away from him and is prepared to kill him. In a moment of bravery, C-3PO stands between Luke and Valance, declaring that he is ready to sacrifice himself for his master. Moved by behavior which is typically uncharacteristic for a droid, Valance decides to let them go.

